                    <t:listBibl type="secondary">
                        <t:bibl corresp="http://zotero.org/groups/358366/items/QGQA7X5G"><seg type="encyclopediaArticle"><!-- attributes from original bibl--></seg><t:ptr target="bm:PersoonBalicka2007EnAeMandabba"/><title level="a">Mändabba Mädḫane ʿAläm</title><title type="short">EAe</title><title level="m">Encyclopaedia Aethiopica</title><author><forename>Joachim</forename><surname>Persoon</surname></author><author><forename>Ewa</forename><surname>Balicka-Witakowska</surname></author><editor><forename>Siegbert</forename><surname>Uhlig</surname></editor><pubPlace>Wiesbaden</pubPlace><publisher>Harrassowitz Verlag</publisher><date>2007</date><biblScope unit="volume">III</biblScope><biblScope unit="page">723a-724b</biblScope><note type="tags"><note type="tag">bm:PersoonBalicka2007EnAeMandabba</note></note><note type="tag">bm:PersoonBalicka2007EnAeMandabba</note></t:bibl>
                    </t:listBibl>
                    <t:note>
                        <t:date type="foundation" notBefore="1300" notAfter="1399">14th century</t:date>
                        <t:desc type="foundation">It was allegedly founded in the <t:date notBefore="1300" notAfter="1399">14th cent.</t:date> by <t:roleName type="title">ʾabuna</t:roleName>
                            <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS10253Yasay">Yāsāy</t:persName>, son of <t:roleName type="title">ʾaṣe</t:roleName>
                            <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS1854Amdase">ʿAmda Ṣǝyon I</t:persName>.</t:desc>
                        <t:ab type="history">The main church established by <t:roleName type="title">ʾabuna</t:roleName>
                            <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS10253Yasay">Yāsāy</t:persName> seems to have survived
                            most invasions undamaged and, according to the tradition, in the <t:date notBefore="1500" notAfter="1599">16th cent.</t:date>, <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS1522Ahmadb">Aḥmad b. Ibrāhīm al-Ġāzī</t:persName> was chased
                            away from the monastery by <t:roleName type="title">archangels</t:roleName>
                            <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS4377Gabriel">Gabriel</t:persName> and <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS7049Michael">Michael</t:persName>. In the <t:date notBefore="1600" notAfter="1699">17th cent.</t:date> the church was
                            renovated by <t:roleName type="title">ʾaṣe</t:roleName>
                            <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS4015Fasilada">Fāsiladas</t:persName>. This monastery was
                            an important centre of learning and played a significant role in the
                            religious disputes between Tawāḥǝdo and Qǝbāt teaching. Mandābbā Madḫāne
                            ʿĀlam was not affected by the Mahdist invasions in the <t:date notBefore="1800" notAfter="1899">19th cent.</t:date>. In the <t:date notBefore="1900" notAfter="1999">20th cent.</t:date>, <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS7006Menilek">Mǝnilǝk II</t:persName> and <t:roleName type="title">empress</t:roleName>
                            <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS10671Zawditu">Zawditu</t:persName> donated books to the
                            library of the monastery, while <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS5226haylase">Ḫāyla
                                Śǝllāse I</t:persName> provided for an extensive renovation of the old
                            church and <t:roleName type="title">ǝtege</t:roleName>
                            <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS6642MananAs">Manan ʾAsfāw</t:persName> financed an
                            adjoining church for women. The church survived the Darg period fairly
                            well.</t:ab>
                        <t:ab type="tabot">
                            <t:measure>1</t:measure>
                            <t:desc>In <t:date when="2006">2006</t:date>, some fragments depicting the
                                scenes of the Passion were discovered inside an old manbara
                                tābot.</t:desc>
                  </t:ab>
                        <t:ab type="description">Located on the north shore of the lak, close to
                                <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC3589Gorgor">Gorgorā</t:placeName>, Mandābbā Madḫāne
                            ʿĀlam is the second largest monastery of the lake <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC5888Tana">Ṭānā</t:placeName> region after <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/INS0329DE">Dāgā ʾƎsṭifānos</t:placeName>. It had lands in the
                            districts of <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC6565Sowit">Sowit</t:placeName>, <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC1314Alafa">ʾAlafā</t:placeName> and <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC6566Takwesa">Takʷǝsā</t:placeName> and, although they much
                            reduced over time, they remained much greater than those of most other
                            monasteries. The church was richly endowed and painted and still
                            preserves paintings and objects of value. The paintings currently in the
                            church were executed in <t:date when="1983">1983</t:date> by <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS9332Tawalda">Tawalda Gabra Bǝrhan</t:persName>. The monastery
                            holds a collection of manuscripts including <t:ref type="work" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT1933Mashaf">Maṣḥāfa Ḥāwi</t:ref>, a short history of the
                            monastery and a recently produced paper copy of the same produced by
                                <t:roleName type="title">abbot</t:roleName>
                            <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS10571Zamanfa">Za-Manfas Qǝddus Gabra
                                Ṣādǝqān</t:persName>, the illumnated <t:date notBefore="1300" notAfter="1399">14th cent.</t:date>
                            <t:ref type="work" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT1019Actsof">Acts of the Apostles</t:ref> and
                            the <t:date notBefore="1700" notAfter="1799">18th cent.</t:date>
                            <t:ref type="work" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT1295Dersan">Dǝrsāna Mikāʾel</t:ref> with 54
                            miniatures and the portrait on fols. 4v and 14v of its former owners,
                            the noble couple <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS4289GabraLe">Gabra Lǝʾul</t:persName>
                            and <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS6701Marata">Marʿāta Giyorgis</t:persName>.</t:ab>
                    </t:note>
                </t:place>
                
